    <p>MILLER: But the people who were there early on will have the close relationship and be able to walk in and see the member or his staff whenever he or she wants.</p>
    <p>OVERBY: And politics is all about networking. David Rehr is a business executive and former lobbyist. He says new lawmakers need to meet key people around town: lobbyists, advisers, moneymen...</p>
    <p>DAVID REHR: Because at some point, they'll help you either with your issues or getting reelected or being perceived as being more influential by other Washingtonians, so you can try to enact more change in the government.</p>
